04320nam a22005535i 9781477328514DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773285147 a10.7560/3285072doi  a(DE-B1597)673128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN2062b.R39 2024 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a792.02/8223/eng/202304241 aRawlins, Justin Owen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagining the Method :bReception, Identity, and American Screen Performance /cJustin Owen Rawlins. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b27 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tINTRODUCTION What We Talk about When We Talk about the Method -- tCHAPTER 1 Methodists and Method-ists: Primordial Ideas of Methodness -- tCHAPTER 2 Acting a Foil: John Wayne, Marlon Brando, and the Othering of Methodness -- tCHAPTER 3 James Dean’s Story: Posthumous Reception and Methodness Memorialized -- tCHAPTER 4 History in Hysteria: John Garfield and the Limits of Methodness -- tCHAPTER 5 Illogical Tomatoes to Inscrutable Feats: Methodness to the Present -- tCONCLUSION Facing a Future Methodness -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA revisionist history of Method acting that connects the popular reception of “methodness” to entrenched understandings of screen performance still dominating American film discourse today. Only one performance style has dominated the lexicon of the casual moviegoer: “Method acting.” The first reception-based analysis of film acting, Imagining the Method investigates how popular understandings of the so-called Method—what its author Justin Rawlins calls "methodness"—created an exclusive brand for white, male actors while associating such actors with rebellion and marginalization. Drawing on extensive archival research, the book maps the forces giving shape to methodness and policing its boundaries. Imagining the Method traces the primordial conditions under which the Method was conceived. It explores John Garfield's tenuous relationship with methodness due to his identity. It considers the links between John Wayne's reliance on "anti-Method" stardom and Marlon Brando and James Dean's ascribed embodiment of Method features. It dissects contemporary emphases on transformation and considers the implications of methodness in the encoding of AI performers. Altogether, Justin Rawlins offers a revisionist history of the Method that shines a light on the cultural politics of methodness and the still-dominant assumptions about race, gender, and screen actors and acting that inform how we talk about performance and performers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMethod actingxHistory. 0aMethod actingxInfluence. 0aMethod actingxPress coverage. 0aMotion picture actingxHistory. 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion picture audienceszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32850740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477328514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477328514/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles